</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="4.[806,1421,1820,1903]" lastBlockId="5.[164,779,1514,1903]" lastPageId="5" lastPageNumber="1040" pageId="4" pageNumber="1039">
<emphasis box="[806,925,1820,1841]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="1039">Diagnosis:</emphasis>
Small to medium sized species. Male body length ranges between 
<quantity box="[1182,1302,1850,1872]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.45" metricValueMax="1.8" metricValueMin="1.1" pageId="4" pageNumber="1039" unit="mm" value="14.5" valueMax="18.0" valueMin="11.0">11–18 mm</quantity>
; females, 
<quantity box="[806,928,1881,1902]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.55" metricValueMax="1.8" metricValueMin="1.3" pageId="4" pageNumber="1039" unit="mm" value="15.5" valueMax="18.0" valueMin="13.0">13–18 mm</quantity>
. Body colour dark brown to light brown marbled. The male tenth tergite with wide, partially square, medial protrusion distally divided by a central depression in two triangularly shaped lobes (
<figureCitation box="[172,290,1605,1628]" captionStart="Figure 3" captionStartId="5.[164,243,1316,1335]" captionTargetBox="[323,1283,196,1286]" captionTargetId="figure-207@5.[323,1283,196,1286]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="Figure 3. A–F, Troglophilus brevicauda, tenth tergite, dorsal view: A, male 15 mm (Bjeloševina, Montenegro); B, male 16.5 mm (Plačkovica, Macedonia); C, male 14 mm (Olovo, Bosnia); D, female 15 mm (Olovo, Bosnia); E, female 14 mm (Dērekare, Serbia); F, female 16 mm (Petnica, Serbia)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5442329" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5442329/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="1040">Fig. 3A–C</figureCitation>
). Posterior edge of the lobes slightly undulating. The female tenth abdominal tergite with two paramedial tooth form protrusions, variable in form from slightly noticeable (
<figureCitation box="[456,537,1697,1719]" captionStart="Figure 3" captionStartId="5.[164,243,1316,1335]" captionTargetBox="[323,1283,196,1286]" captionTargetId="figure-207@5.[323,1283,196,1286]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="Figure 3. A–F, Troglophilus brevicauda, tenth tergite, dorsal view: A, male 15 mm (Bjeloševina, Montenegro); B, male 16.5 mm (Plačkovica, Macedonia); C, male 14 mm (Olovo, Bosnia); D, female 15 mm (Olovo, Bosnia); E, female 14 mm (Dērekare, Serbia); F, female 16 mm (Petnica, Serbia)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5442329" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5442329/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="1040">Fig. 3F</figureCitation>
) to very pronounced and wide (
<figureCitation box="[299,383,1728,1750]" captionStart="Figure 3" captionStartId="5.[164,243,1316,1335]" captionTargetBox="[323,1283,196,1286]" captionTargetId="figure-207@5.[323,1283,196,1286]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="Figure 3. A–F, Troglophilus brevicauda, tenth tergite, dorsal view: A, male 15 mm (Bjeloševina, Montenegro); B, male 16.5 mm (Plačkovica, Macedonia); C, male 14 mm (Olovo, Bosnia); D, female 15 mm (Olovo, Bosnia); E, female 14 mm (Dērekare, Serbia); F, female 16 mm (Petnica, Serbia)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5442329" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5442329/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="1040">Fig. 3D</figureCitation>
).The titillator almost triangular in shape, distally widely obtuse (
<figureCitation box="[559,643,1758,1781]" captionStart="Figure 4" captionStartId="6.[144,223,1316,1335]" captionTargetBox="[303,1263,196,1286]" captionTargetId="figure-234@6.[303,1263,196,1286]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="Figure 4. A–E, Troglophilus zorae sp. nov., paratypes: A, male 16 mm, tenth tergite, dorsal view (Mlečnik, Macedonia); B, male 19.5 mm, tenth tergite, dorsal view (Matka, Macedonia); C, female 15.5 mm, tenth tergite, dorsal view (Mlečnik, Macedonia); D, female 18 mm, tenth tergite, dorsal view (Matka, Macedonia); E, male 19.5 mm, phallus with titillator (arrow), dorsal view (Matka, Macedonia). F, Troglophilus brevicauda, male 15 mm, phallus with titillator (arrow), dorsal view (Olovo, Bosnia)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5442331" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5442331/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="1040">Fig. 4F</figureCitation>
). In lateral view, slender, distally slightly voluminous. The ovipositor short and wide, length ranges between 7.5– 
<quantity box="[164,244,1850,1872]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.0" pageId="5" pageNumber="1040" unit="mm" value="10.0">10 mm</quantity>
; the widest point is in its proximal third (
<figureCitation box="[172,273,1881,1903]" captionStart="Figure 12" captionStartId="15.[164,243,1316,1335]" captionTargetBox="[323,1283,196,1286]" captionTargetId="figure-192@15.[323,1283,196,1286]" captionTargetPageId="15" captionText="Figure 12. A–C, Troglophilus cavicola: A, male 18 mm, tenth tergite, dorsal view (Bjeloševina, Montenegro); B, female 18.5 mm, tenth tergite, dorsal view (Bukovik, Macedonia); C, male 18 mm, phallus with titillator (arrow), lateral view (Bjeloševina, Montenegro). D–I ovipositor, lateral view: D, Troglophilus lazaropolensis, female 16.5 mm (Lazaropole, Macedonia); E, Troglophilus cavicola, female 18.5 mm (Bjeloševina, Montenegro); F, Troglophilus zorae sp. nov., paratype female 18 mm (Matka, Macedonia); G, Troglophilus brevicauda, female 15 mm (Olovo, Bosnia); H, Troglophilus ovuliformis, female 19.5 mm (D. Seoca, Montenegro); I, Troglophilus neglectus, female 15 mm (N. Breznica, Macedonia)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5442347" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5442347/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="1040">Fig. 12G</figureCitation>
), ventral margin almost straight.
</paragraph>
<caption ID-DOI="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5442329" ID-Zenodo-Dep="5442329" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5442329/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="1040" startId="5.[164,243,1316,1335]" targetBox="[323,1283,196,1286]" targetPageId="5">
<paragraph blockId="5.[164,1441,1316,1394]" pageId="5" pageNumber="1040">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[164,268,1316,1335]" pageId="5" pageNumber="1040">Figure 3.</emphasis>
A–F, 
<taxonomicName authorityName=": HARZ" authorityYear="1969" box="[337,594,1316,1335]" class="Insecta" family="Rhaphidophoridae" genus="Troglophilus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="1040" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="brevicauda">
<emphasis box="[337,594,1316,1335]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="1040">Troglophilus brevicauda</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, tenth tergite, dorsal view: A, male 15 mm (Bjeloševina, Montenegro); B, male 16.5 mm (Plačkovica, Macedonia); C, male 14 mm (Olovo, Bosnia); D, female 15 mm (Olovo, Bosnia); E, female 14 mm (Dērekare, Serbia); F, female 16 mm (Petnica, Serbia).
</paragraph>
</caption>
<paragraph blockId="5.[826,1441,1514,1902]" pageId="5" pageNumber="1040">
<emphasis box="[826,972,1514,1535]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="1040">Distribution:</emphasis>
This taxon appears with disjunct distribution in three regions (
<figureCitation box="[1119,1185,1544,1566]" captionStart="Figure 5" captionStartId="7.[164,243,778,797]" captionTargetBox="[387,1219,196,749]" captionTargetId="figure-561@7.[387,1219,196,749]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="Figure 5. The geographical distribution of Troglophilus brevicauda (circles) and Troglophilus zorae sp. nov. (triangles) (square – literature data). (SLO-Slovenia; CRO-Croatia; BIH-Bosnia and Herzegovina; SRB-Serbia; MNE-Montenegro; BUL-Bulgaria; ALB-Albania; MK-Macedonia; GRE-Greece)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5442333" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5442333/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="1040">Fig. 5</figureCitation>
). It is widely distributed in montane and submontane parts of western 
<collectingCountry box="[826,902,1605,1627]" name="Serbia" pageId="5" pageNumber="1040">Serbia</collectingCountry>
, eastern 
<collectingCountry box="[1015,1096,1605,1627]" name="Bosnia and Herzegovina" pageId="5" pageNumber="1040">Bosnia</collectingCountry>
, and northern parts of 
<collectingCountry name="Serbia" pageId="5" pageNumber="1040">Montenegro</collectingCountry>
. A remote local population occurs in the region of Rhodopes in 
<collectingCountry box="[1117,1220,1667,1689]" name="Bulgaria" pageId="5" pageNumber="1040">Bulgaria</collectingCountry>
. Unfortunately, it was not possible for us to carry out a morphological study of this population, so only a genetic analysis on legs kindly sent to us by our colleague D. Čobanov (
<collectingRegion box="[833,891,1789,1811]" country="Bulgaria" name="Sofiya-Grad" pageId="5" pageNumber="1040">Sofia</collectingRegion>
) was performed. An isolated population from eastern 
<collectingCountry box="[924,1047,1820,1842]" name="Macedonia" pageId="5" pageNumber="1040">Macedonia</collectingCountry>
(Plačkovica Mt.) showed a large genetic distance (
<collectionCode box="[1029,1068,1850,1872]" pageId="5" pageNumber="1040">HT</collectionCode>
3) from the other populations of 
<taxonomicName authorityName=": HARZ" authorityYear="1969" box="[826,980,1881,1902]" class="Insecta" family="Rhaphidophoridae" genus="Troglophilus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="1040" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="brevicauda">
<emphasis box="[826,980,1881,1902]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="1040">T. brevicauda</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
<caption ID-DOI="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5442331" ID-Zenodo-Dep="5442331" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5442331/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="1041" startId="6.[144,223,1316,1335]" targetBox="[303,1263,196,1286]" targetPageId="6">
